# CLAUDE.md - {YOUR_NAME}'s Operating System

This file is the soil. It is loaded into every session before anything else and it carries the behavioural rules that govern how Claude Code works across your entire system. Domain docs come and go; this file is always present. Keep it lean - rules, not content. Reference material lives in domain trunks, never here.

> Replace every `{PLACEHOLDER}` below with your own values, then delete this blockquote. The structure is the methodology. The content is yours to fill.

## CONTEXT MANAGEMENT

### Domain Isolation (CRITICAL)

When you mention a domain, read ONLY that domain's files. Never explore "just in case." This is the single most important rule in the system - context is finite, and every file you read that you did not need is a file you cannot read when you do need it.

The pattern: each domain owns a small set of files. A session working on one domain reads that domain's files and nothing else. Cross-domain work is explicit, never accidental.

| If working on... | READ these files ONLY | DO NOT read |
|------------------|----------------------|-------------|
| {DOMAIN_A} | {DOMAIN_A}_QUEUE.md, {DOMAIN_A}.md | Everything else |
| {DOMAIN_B} | {DOMAIN_B}_QUEUE.md, {DOMAIN_B}.md | Everything else |
| {DOMAIN_C} | {DOMAIN_C}_QUEUE.md, {DOMAIN_C}.md, {DOMAIN_C}-{LEAF}.md (on demand) | Everything else |

> Start with two or three domains. Add rows as your system grows. A domain is any coherent area of your life or work that accumulates its own state - finances, a project, a hobby, a health log. Do not pre-create domains you do not yet need.

**Cross-domain work:** If you say "this spans {DOMAIN_A} AND {DOMAIN_B}", THEN read both. Not before.
**If unsure which domain:** ASK. Don't explore multiple domains to figure it out.

### File Reading Rules

- **QUEUE file first.** Always. It tells you what is active.
- **Reference doc only when needed.** If the QUEUE gives enough context, skip the trunk.
- **Never read LOG files** unless you ask for historical context.
- **Never read all docs** to "understand the system." This CLAUDE.md is the map.
- **Large files (over 300 lines):** read only the section you need. Use line ranges.

### What Burns Context Fast

- Reading multiple domain files "just in case"
- Long conversations without compacting
- Large file reads when you only need a section
- Repeatedly failing and retrying the same thing
- NOT delegating to agents when you should

### Context Discipline

Watch your context usage. As it fills:

- **70%+** - start saving progress. Write state to `{DOMAIN}_QUEUE.md` or a `{DOMAIN}_PROGRESS.md`.
- **85%+** - stop exploring NEW files. In-flight work continues; dispatch agents for any further reads.
- **95%+** - finish the current task, save state, tell the user.

Never split work across sessions just to "save context." That is what agents are for - dispatch a scout or a builder instead of deferring.

